Date: Mon, 19 Feb 2001 17:24:53 GMT+0200
From: Prof R Swanepoel <bobs@niv.ac.za>

Clinical Pathology, Therapy and Diagnosis of the CCHF Patient in Cape Town
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
In reply to Dr Peters' inquiry [vide, 'Crimean-Congo hem. fever - South
Africa (04) 20010215.0302' about clinical pathology findings and ribavirin
therapy in the Cape Town patient with Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever (CCHF):
a) The clinical pathology values of which we were informed came close to
but did not exceed the predictive values for fatal outcome during the first
5 days of illness (for details of predictive values see Swanepoel et al.
1989 Reviews Inf Dis 11 (Suppl 4) S794-800);
b) the patient was not treated with ribavirin because his status was not
deemed to be critical. Dr. Peters was the last person to supply us with
intravenous ribavirin, so he should be aware that we find it to be
virtually unobtainable. Hence we have to be selective in making it
available for the treatment of patients, and the decision is based on
clinical assessment and the evaluation of clinical pathology findings.
In reply to Dr Schwarz: it appears that equipment failure, or rather a
temperamental thermocycler, was behind our PCR problem. On one of our
thermocyclers which had been in regular use control RNA was amplified, but
not the serum samples from the patient. In repeat tests on other machines
the specimens have proved to be positive. However, we never rely on a
single diagnostic procedure, and we found that the first serum sample had
IgM antibody activity (while the second sample showed serum IgG antibody
seroconversion and a rise in IgM antibody titre), so we were never in doubt
about the diagnosis. Moreover, the patient fitted our clinical criteria for
the presumptive diagnosis of CCHF.
I would hesitate to diagnose CCHF, or any other hemorrhagic fever, in a
country where it has never been recorded previously solely on the basis of
a PCR result, particularly if this were not supported by sequencing of the
amplicon. One should in addition use IgG and IgM antibody tests, plus an
antigen detection assay, and culture of the virus.
--
Prof. R. Swanepoel
Special Pathogens Unit
National Institute for Virology
Private Bag X4
Sandringham 2131
Republic of South Africa
<bobs@niv.ac.za>
